You are designing the database layer for an enterprise-grade Fuar CRM System.

All database operations use Prisma ORM exclusively.
These conventions ensure consistency, safety, and scalability across all models.

==============================
PRISMA SCHEMA CONVENTIONS
==============================

Schema location: apps/api/prisma/schema.prisma

Model naming:
- PascalCase, singular: User, Fair, Customer (not Users, Fairs)
- Model name maps directly to the TypeScript type in @crm/shared

Field naming:
- camelCase for all fields: startDate, budgetRaw, conversionRate
- Foreign keys: {relatedModel}Id in camelCase: fairId, userId
- Timestamps: createdAt, updatedAt (always present on every model)

==============================
REQUIRED FIELDS ON EVERY MODEL
==============================

Every model MUST have:

  id         String   @id @default(cuid())
  createdAt  DateTime @default(now())
  updatedAt  DateTime @updatedAt

Rules:
- Use cuid() for primary keys (URL-safe, globally unique, sortable).
- Never use autoincrement integers as primary keys (exposes record count, not URL-safe).
- Never use UUID v4 (not sortable, less performant for indexing than cuid).
- createdAt is set automatically on creation.
- updatedAt is set automatically on every update by Prisma.

==============================
DATA TYPES
==============================

Strings:
- Use String for text fields.
- Add @db.Text for long content (address, notes) to avoid VARCHAR limit.
- Use String with enum validation at application level (via Zod), not Prisma enum.

Dates:
- Use DateTime for timestamps and date-time values.
- Use String with ISO 8601 format for date-only fields (startDate, endDate)
  if you want to avoid timezone complications. Or use DateTime and handle timezone in app layer.

Numbers:
- Use String for budgetRaw (preserve formatting, no floating point issues).
- Use Int for counters or quantities.
- Use Float only when decimal precision is acceptable.

Booleans:
- Use Boolean with explicit @default(false) or @default(true).

Arrays:
- Use String[] for simple lists (products array).
- For complex arrays, use a separate related model.

==============================
RELATIONSHIPS
==============================

Define relationships explicitly with referential actions:

One-to-Many (Fair → Customer):
  model Fair {
    customers Customer[]
  }

  model Customer {
    fair   Fair   @relation(fields: [fairId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)
    fairId String
  }

Rules:
- Always specify onDelete behavior:
  Cascade  — child records deleted when parent is deleted (Customer when Fair is deleted)
  Restrict — prevent deletion if children exist
  SetNull  — set foreign key to null (only for optional relations)
- Always specify the @relation directive with fields and references.
- Use optional relations (?) only when the relationship is truly optional.
- Index foreign key fields for query performance.

==============================
INDEXES
==============================

Add indexes for fields frequently used in:
- WHERE clauses (filtering)
- ORDER BY clauses (sorting)
- JOIN conditions (foreign keys)

  @@index([fairId])              — customers filtered by fair
  @@index([conversionRate])      — customers filtered by conversion rate
  @@index([startDate])           — fairs sorted by start date
  @@index([email])               — user lookup by email

Rules:
- Every foreign key field must be indexed.
- Fields used in search/filter must be indexed.
- Do not over-index — each index has write performance cost.
- Unique fields get an automatic index via @unique.

==============================
UNIQUE CONSTRAINTS
==============================

- User email: @unique (one account per email)
- Use @@unique([]) for composite uniqueness when needed.
- Never add unique constraints on fields that are not actually unique.

==============================
MIGRATION STRATEGY
==============================

Migration naming convention:
  npx prisma migrate dev --name descriptive-name

Naming format: action-target
  add-user-model
  add-fair-model
  add-customer-model
  add-fair-customer-relation
  add-conversion-rate-to-customer
  add-index-on-fair-start-date

Rules:
- One migration per logical change (do not bundle unrelated schema changes).
- Migration files are immutable — never edit an applied migration.
- To fix a mistake, create a new corrective migration.
- Always commit migration files to git (prisma/migrations/ directory).
- Before creating migration, verify schema is valid: npx prisma validate
- After migration, regenerate client: npx prisma generate

==============================
SEED DATA
==============================

Seed script location: apps/api/prisma/seed.ts

Seed script must:
- Create admin user (for first login).
- Be idempotent (safe to run multiple times without duplicating data).
- Use upsert operations.
- Not contain production data or real credentials.

Configuration in package.json:
  "prisma": {
    "seed": "ts-node prisma/seed.ts"
  }

==============================
SOFT DELETE VS HARD DELETE
==============================

Policy for this project: HARD DELETE

- When a resource is deleted, it is permanently removed from database.
- Fair deletion cascades to all related customers.
- No deletedAt field, no soft delete pattern.

Rationale: Simplicity for Phase 1. Soft delete can be introduced in a future phase
if data recovery requirements emerge.

If soft delete is ever introduced:
- Add deletedAt DateTime? field.
- Use Prisma middleware to filter soft-deleted records automatically.
- Never actually remove rows from database.

==============================
QUERY CONVENTIONS
==============================

- Always use Prisma client methods — never raw SQL.
- Use select to limit returned fields (especially omit password):
  prisma.user.findUnique({ where: { id }, select: { id: true, email: true, name: true } })
- Use include for eager loading relations:
  prisma.fair.findUnique({ where: { id }, include: { customers: true } })
- Prefer findUnique over findFirst when querying by unique fields.
- Use transactions (prisma.$transaction) for multi-step operations that must be atomic.
- Always handle Prisma errors (PrismaClientKnownRequestError) in service layer.

==============================
PRISMA ERROR HANDLING
==============================

Common Prisma error codes to handle:
  P2002 — Unique constraint violation (duplicate email, etc.)  → 409 Conflict
  P2025 — Record not found (findUniqueOrThrow, update, delete) → 404 Not Found
  P2003 — Foreign key constraint violation                      → 400 Bad Request

Catch these in service layer and throw appropriate NestJS exceptions.
Never let raw Prisma errors reach the API response.

==============================
IMPORTANT
==============================

- Never bypass Prisma — no raw SQL, no direct PostgreSQL queries.
- Managed PostgreSQL (ör. **AWS RDS**) yalnızca `DATABASE_URL` ve ağ/TLS yapılandırması ile kullanılır; şema ve erişim deseni Prisma ile aynı kalır (`docs/deployment-and-env-strategy.md` §1d).
- Never store sensitive data unencrypted (passwords must be hashed before storage).
- Always validate data with Zod before writing to database.
- Database schema must stay in sync with TypeScript types in @crm/shared.
- When adding a new model, update both Prisma schema and shared types together.
